# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: global-illumination
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Areas that lie outside of the ceiling lamp's direct light lack definition.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] For example, the lamp's housing appears completely uniform.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Without the ambient light added into the render, it would appear uniformly black.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Light is reflected by surfaces, and colored light transfers from one surface to another.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Notice how color from the red wall and green wall (not visible) reflects onto other surfaces in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] projected onto the red wall from light passing through the glass sphere.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Theoretically, reflections, refractions, transparency, and shadows are all examples of global illumination, because when simulating them, one object affects the rendering of another (as opposed to an object being affected only by a direct source of light).
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] In practice, however, only the simulation of diffuse inter-reflection or caustics is called global illumination, especially in real-time settings.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Global illumination is a key aspect to the realism of a 3D scene.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Naive 3D lighting will only take into account direct light, meaning any light which radiates off a light source and bounces directly into the virtual camera.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Shadows will appear completely dark, due to light not interacting with any other surface before it reaches the camera.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] As this is not what occurs in real life, we perceive the resulting image as incomplete.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Applying full global illumination allows for the missing effects that makes an image feel more natural.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] However, global illumination is computationally more expensive and consequently much slower to generate.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] The algorithms used to calculate the distribution of light energy between surfaces of a scene are closely related to heat transfer simulations performed using finite-element methods in engineering design.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Achieving accurate computation of global illumination in real-time remains difficult.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] On one end, the diffuse inter-reflection component of global illumination is sometimes approximated by an "ambient" term in the lighting equation, which is also called "ambient lighting" or "ambient color" in 3D software.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Though this method is one of the cheapest ways to simulate indirect lighting, when used alone it does not provide an adequately realistic effect.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Ambient lighting is known to "flatten" shadows in 3D scenes, making the overall visual effect more bland.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Beyond ambient lighting, techniques which trace the path of light accurately have historically been either too slow for consumer hardware or limited to static and precomputed environments.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] This proves problematic, as most applications allow for input from a user that can affect their surroundings, and the precalculation steps may introduce constraints upon the artists.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Consequently, research has been dedicated to finding a balance between adequate performance, accurate visual results, and interactivity.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Starting with Nvidia's RTX 20 series, consumer graphics hardware has been extended to allow for ray tracing computations to be performed in real time through hardware acceleration.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] This has allowed for further improvements, as applications can now harness the power of this acceleration to provide not only precise lighting results, but the ability to affect said lighting dynamically.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Some content that has taken advantage of this capability includes Cyberpunk 2077, Indiana Jones and the Great Circle, and Alan Wake 2, among others.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] For an overview of the current state of real-time global illumination, see or.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Algorithms which attempt to simulate global illumination are numerical approximations of the rendering equation.
[src:global-illumination/global-illumination] Well-known algorithms for computing global illumination include path tracing, photon mapping and radiosity.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The amount of light transported is measured by **flux density**, or luminous flux per unit area on the point of the surface at which it is measured.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport describes the propagation of visible electromagnetic energy in macroscopic environments.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The mathematical theory underpinning light transport can be described by the Hamiltonian approach.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] where H is the Hamiltonian and l is the light energy density.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] In such a form, the light transport equation is identical to the phase space Liouville equation.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Radiometry is the science of measuring electromagnetic radiation, including visible light.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It forms the foundation of light transport theory, which models how light interacts with surfaces, volumes, and media.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Given a surface S, a hemisphere H can be projected onto S to calculate the amount of incoming and outgoing light.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] If a point P is selected at random on the surface S, the amount of incoming and outgoing light can be calculated by its projection onto the hemisphere.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The **hemicube model** works similarly to the hemisphere model, except that a hemicube is projected instead of a hemisphere.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The similarity is only conceptual; the actual calculation, done through numerical integration, has a different form factor.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport theory incorporates both **wave-based** and **particle-based** descriptions of light.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] While wave-based models rely on the principles of Maxwell's equations, particle models use ray optics and Monte Carlo methods to simulate light paths.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The BRDF models how light is reflected on an opaque surface.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It is defined as the ratio of reflected radiance in a given direction to the incident irradiance.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] BRDFs are crucial in light transport theory for simulating realistic material behavior.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Light transport within volumes (e.g., fog, smoke, or translucent objects) is modeled using the radiative transfer equation (RTE).
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Participating media are integral to achieving photorealism in scenes involving volumetric light effects.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Rendering converts a model into an image either by simulating a method, such as light transport, to get physically accurate photorealistic images, or by applying some kind of style as non-photorealistic rendering (NPR).
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] The two basic operations in light transport are transport (how much light gets from one place to another) and scattering (how surfaces interact with light).
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Global illumination simulates all light interactions in a scene, including indirect lighting.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] It employs light transport theory to compute effects such as color bleeding and soft shadows.
[src:global-illumination/light-transport-theory] Unlike photorealistic rendering, non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses light transport models to stylize images, often prioritizing artistic intent over physical accuracy.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] In computer graphics, **photon mapping** is a two-pass global illumination rendering algorithm developed by Henrik Wann Jensen between 1995 and 2001 that approximately solves the rendering equation for integrating light radiance at a given point in space.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Rays from the light source (like photons) and rays from the camera are traced independently until some termination criterion is met, then they are connected in a second step to produce a radiance value.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] The algorithm is used to realistically simulate the interaction of light with different types of objects (similar to other photorealistic rendering techniques).
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Photon mapping can also be extended to more accurate simulations of light, such as spectral rendering.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Progressive photon mapping (PPM) starts with ray tracing and then adds more and more photon mapping passes to provide a progressively more accurate render.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] However, it is a consistent method, and the accuracy of a render can be increased by increasing the number of photons.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] As the number of photons approaches infinity, a render will get closer and closer to the solution of the rendering equation.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Light refracted or reflected causes patterns called caustics, usually visible as concentrated patches of light on nearby surfaces.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For example, as light rays pass through a wine glass sitting on a table, they are refracted and patterns of light are visible on the table.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Photon mapping can trace the paths of individual photons to model where these concentrated patches of light will appear.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Diffuse interreflection is apparent when light from one diffuse object is reflected onto another.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Photon mapping is particularly adept at handling this effect because the algorithm reflects photons from one surface to another based on that surface's bidirectional reflectance distribution function (BRDF), and thus light from one object striking another is a natural result of the method.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Diffuse interreflection was first modeled using radiosity solutions.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Photon mapping differs though in that it separates the light transport from the nature of the geometry in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Color bleed is an example of diffuse interreflection.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Subsurface scattering is the effect evident when light enters a material and is scattered before being absorbed or reflected in a different direction.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Subsurface scattering can accurately be modeled using photon mapping.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] This was the original way Jensen implemented it; however, the method becomes slow for highly scattering materials, and bidirectional surface scattering reflectance distribution functions (BSSRDFs) are more efficient in these situations.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] With photon mapping, light packets called *photons* are sent out into the scene from the light sources.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Whenever a photon intersects with a surface, the intersection point and incoming direction are stored in a cache called the *photon map*.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Typically, two photon maps are created for a scene: one especially for caustics and a global one for other light.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] After intersecting the surface, a probability for either reflecting, absorbing, or transmitting/refracting is given by the material.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] A Monte Carlo method called *Russian roulette* is used to choose one of these actions.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] If the photon is absorbed, no new direction is given, and tracing for that photon ends.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] If the photon reflects, the surface's bidirectional reflectance distribution function is used to determine the ratio of reflected radiance.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Finally, if the photon is transmitting, a function for its direction is given depending upon the nature of the transmission.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Once the photon map is constructed (or during construction), it is typically arranged in a manner that is optimal for the k-nearest neighbor algorithm, as photon look-up time depends on the spatial distribution of the photons.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] The photon map is then stored on disk or in memory for later usage.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] In this step of the algorithm, the photon map created in the first pass is used to estimate the radiance of every pixel of the output image.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For each pixel, the scene is ray traced until the closest surface of intersection is found.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] At this point, the rendering equation is used to calculate the surface radiance leaving the point of intersection in the direction of the ray that struck it.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] To facilitate efficiency, the equation is decomposed into four separate factors: direct illumination, specular reflection, caustics, and soft indirect illumination.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For an accurate estimate of direct illumination, a ray is traced from the point of intersection to each light source.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] As long as a ray does not intersect another object, the light source is used to calculate the direct illumination.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For an approximate estimate of indirect illumination, the photon map is used to calculate the radiance contribution.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Specular reflection can be, in most cases, calculated using ray tracing procedures (as it handles reflections well).
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] The contribution to the surface radiance from caustics is calculated using the caustics photon map directly.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] The number of photons in this map must be sufficiently large, as the map is the only source for caustics information in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For soft indirect illumination, radiance is calculated using the photon map directly.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] This contribution, however, does not need to be as accurate as the caustics contribution and thus uses the global photon map.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] In order to calculate surface radiance at an intersection point, one of the cached photon maps is used.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] Let S be the sphere that contains these N photons.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] For each photon, divide the amount of flux (real photons) that the photon represents by the area of S and multiply by the BRDF applied to that photon.
[src:global-illumination/photon-mapping] The sum of those results for each photon represents total surface radiance returned by the surface intersection in the direction of the ray that struck it.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In 3D computer graphics, **radiosity** is an application of the finite element method to solving the rendering equation for scenes with surfaces that reflect light diffusely.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity is a global illumination algorithm in the sense that the illumination arriving on a surface comes not just directly from the light sources, but also from other surfaces reflecting light.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity is viewpoint independent, which increases the calculations involved, but makes them useful for all viewpoints.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity methods were first developed in about 1950 in the engineering field of heat transfer.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] They were later refined specifically for the problem of rendering computer graphics in 1984–1985 by researchers at Cornell University and Hiroshima University.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Notable commercial radiosity engines are Enlighten by Geomerics (used for games including Battlefield 3 and Need for Speed: The Run); 3ds Max; form•Z; LightWave 3D and the Electric Image Animation System.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The inclusion of radiosity calculations in the rendering process often lends an added element of realism to the finished scene, because of the way it mimics real-world phenomena.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The image on the left was rendered with a typical **direct illumination renderer**.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The image on the right was rendered using a **radiosity algorithm**.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] There is only **one source of light**: an image of the sky placed outside the window.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Soft shadows are visible on the floor, and subtle lighting effects are noticeable around the room.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Furthermore, the red color from the carpet has bled onto the grey walls, giving them a slightly warm appearance.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] None of these effects were specifically chosen or designed by the artist.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The surfaces of the scene to be rendered are each divided up into one or more smaller surfaces (patches).
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] A view factor (also known as *form factor*) is computed for each pair of patches; it is a coefficient describing how well the patches can see each other.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Patches that are far away from each other, or oriented at oblique angles relative to one another, will have smaller view factors.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] If other patches are in the way, the view factor will be reduced or zero, depending on whether the occlusion is partial or total.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The view factors are used as coefficients in a linear system of rendering equations.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Solving this system yields the radiosity, or brightness, of each patch, taking into account diffuse interreflections and soft shadows.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Progressive radiosity solves the system iteratively with intermediate radiosity values for the patch, corresponding to bounce levels.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] That is, after each iteration, we know how the scene looks after one light bounce, after two passes, two bounces, and so forth.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is useful for getting an interactive preview of the scene.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Also, the user can stop the iterations once the image looks good enough, rather than wait for the computation to numerically converge.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Another common method for solving the radiosity equation is "shooting radiosity," which iteratively solves the radiosity equation by "shooting" light from the patch with the most energy at each step.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After the first pass, only those patches which are in direct line of sight of a light-emitting patch will be illuminated.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After the second pass, more patches will become illuminated as the light begins to bounce around the scene.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The scene continues to grow brighter and eventually reaches a steady state.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The basic radiosity method has its basis in the theory of thermal radiation, since radiosity relies on computing the amount of light energy transferred among surfaces.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In order to simplify computations, the method assumes that all scattering is perfectly diffuse.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Surfaces are typically discretized into quadrilateral or triangular elements over which a piecewise polynomial function is defined.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] After this breakdown, the amount of light energy transfer can be computed by using the known reflectivity of the reflecting patch, combined with the view factor of the two patches.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This dimensionless quantity is computed from the geometric orientation of two patches, and can be thought of as the fraction of the total possible emitting area of the first patch which is covered by the second.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] where *Fij* is the geometrical view factor for the radiation leaving *j* and hitting patch *i*.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This equation can then be applied to each patch.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The equation is monochromatic, so color radiosity rendering requires calculation for each of the required colors.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This gives the full "infinite bounce" solution for B directly.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However the number of calculations to compute the matrix solution scales according to *n*3, where *n* is the number of patches.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This becomes prohibitive for realistically large values of *n*.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Instead, the equation can more readily be solved iteratively, by repeatedly applying the single-bounce update formula above.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Formally, this is a solution of the matrix equation by Jacobi iteration.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Because the reflectivities ρi are less than 1, this scheme converges quickly, typically requiring only a handful of iterations to produce a reasonable solution.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Other standard iterative methods for matrix equation solutions can also be used, for example the Gauss–Seidel method, where updated values for each patch are used in the calculation as soon as they are computed, rather than all being updated synchronously at the end of each sweep.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The solution can also be tweaked to iterate over each of the sending elements in turn in its main outermost loop for each update, rather than each of the receiving patches.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is known as the *shooting* variant of the algorithm, as opposed to the *gathering* variant.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is sometimes known as the "power" formulation, since it is now the total transmitted power of each element that is being updated, rather than its radiosity.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The view factor *F*ij itself can be calculated in a number of ways.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Early methods used a *hemicube* (an imaginary cube centered upon the first surface to which the second surface was projected, devised by Michael F.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The surface of the hemicube was divided into pixel-like squares, for each of which a view factor can be readily calculated analytically.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The full form factor could then be approximated by adding up the contribution from each of the pixel-like squares.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The projection onto the hemicube, which could be adapted from standard methods for determining the visibility of polygons, also solved the problem of intervening patches partially obscuring those behind.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However all this was quite computationally expensive, because ideally form factors must be derived for every possible pair of patches, leading to a quadratic increase in computation as the number of patches increased.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This can be reduced somewhat by using a binary space partitioning tree to reduce the amount of time spent determining which patches are completely hidden from others in complex scenes; but even so, the time spent to determine the form factor still typically scales as *n* log *n*.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] New methods include adaptive integration.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The form factors *F*ij themselves are not in fact explicitly needed in either of the update equations; neither to estimate the total intensity Σj *F*ij *B*j gathered from the whole view, nor to estimate how the power *A*j *B*j being radiated is distributed.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Instead, these updates can be estimated by sampling methods, without ever having to calculate form factors explicitly.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Since the mid 1990s such sampling approaches have been the methods most predominantly used for practical radiosity calculations.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The gathered intensity can be estimated by generating a set of samples in the unit circle, lifting these onto the hemisphere, and then seeing what was the radiosity of the element that a ray incoming in that direction would have originated on.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The estimate for the total gathered intensity is then just the average of the radiosities discovered by each ray.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Similarly, in the power formulation, power can be distributed by generating a set of rays from the radiating element in the same way, and spreading the power to be distributed equally between each element a ray hits.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] This is essentially the same distribution that a path-tracing program would sample in tracing back one diffuse reflection step; or that a bidirectional ray-tracing program would sample to achieve one forward diffuse reflection step when light source mapping forwards.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Static, pre-computed radiosity may be displayed in real time via lightmaps using standard rasterization techniques.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Typical radiosity methods only account for light paths of the form LD*E, i.e. paths which start at a light source and make multiple diffuse bounces before reaching the eye.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Although there are several approaches to integrating other illumination effects such as specular and glossy reflections, radiosity-based methods are generally not used to solve the complete rendering equation.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Basic radiosity also has trouble resolving sudden changes in visibility (e.g. hard-edged shadows) because coarse, regular discretization into piecewise constant elements corresponds to a low-pass box filter of the spatial domain.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Discontinuity meshing [1] uses knowledge of visibility events to generate a more intelligent discretization.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Radiosity was perhaps the first rendering algorithm in widespread use which accounted for diffuse indirect lighting.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] However, the three are distinct concepts.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] The radiosity method, in the context of computer graphics, derives from (and is fundamentally the same as) the radiosity method in heat transfer.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] In this context, radiosity is the total radiative flux (both reflected and re-radiated) leaving a surface; this is also sometimes known as radiant exitance.
[src:global-illumination/radiosity-computer-graphics] Calculation of radiosity, rather than surface temperatures, is a key aspect of the radiosity method that permits linear matrix methods to be applied to the problem.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:global-illumination/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
